text: This movie only blames the banks, but they didn't solely cause the housing bubble. It was also caused by government policies and the Federal Reserve.   The Federal Reserve set the interest rate to 1% which caused mortgages to fall. This caused much growth in borrowing and lending.   Then politicians made regulations so that low interest loans had to be extended to people with worse credit ratings. Those people with bad credit ratings couldn't pay the mortgage and that caused the housing bubble.  https://mises.org/library/housing-bubble-4-easy-steps
author: gamevalor

text: Just like 99 Houses - this movie will not get seen.    The average person who hasn't had their house taken does not understand the systemic fraud involved.  They think "why aren't these people in jail?  Good question.  Interestingly enough Iceland had the balls to jail their bankers for the exact same thing that was done here.  We have a congress that is bought and paid for by the banks.  We also have news media that is corporately owned - that's why you will not see much reporting on this either.  20/20 did a little tiny piece on it - look it up they interviewed Lynn Syzmoniak.  Try Googling the term Mortgage Fraud - read - read - read.  It's all out there - it's just not reported on by Fox.

text: This one's going to be a long one:  Newspapers are calling this one a comedy.  Amazing.  "Collateralized Debt Obligation" (CDO)'s being repackaged is NOT necessarily 'completely wrong' . . . in this author's view.  "Debt" existing that is continuing to fail is cause to rescue so that holders of debt don't come a calling with 'Courts' as their prostitute (messenger service -- compliance committee).   Rescuing debt keeps enterprises solvent so that jobs are not lost and local economies do not fail.  Still . . . debt is debt.  No one wants debt.  And debt NEEDS solution.  Is that funny?  Most of the debt's foundation in this scenario is debt held by a boy & a girl deciding between themselves to 'make a go of it'.  Life.  Is 'that' funny?  Perhaps Hollywood would like to play games with each other, B-Rad.  "CDO's"?  CD-owes?  Seedy-oz?  "I've got to break up with this guy."  "He has plenty of seed."  Didn't 'Oz' die?  Is 'that' funny, B-Rad?  Is it funny to Star Jones who likes "rich man".  Is that funny?  Did you know that New York City continues to exist on a 24 hour supply of food that exists everyday on store shelves . . . NOT including anything anyone might have in their kitchens?!?  Is that funny?  Is it funny to muddle the picture amongst circulation control for children of lesser gods?  These are real people who are impacted.  Is that funny?  A Secretary of the Treasury who testifies regularly before Congressional committees using fiscal policy terms to gossip about sexual trysts?  Is that funny?  A press of college graduate, silver-spoons who wet their pencils with their tongues snickering at their Ivy League prowess.  Is that funny?

text: This is one to remember, by far the best movie of 2015, and one of the best I've seen in a long, long time. I think we mustn't underestimate the quality of the acting here, in my opinion, there isn't a single overacted and annoying character, everybody is realistic, and that's something I didn't see coming from a satirical movie. Yeah, I wouldn't count this as a comedy, it's definitely more of a drama/documentary, but it blew my mind on how well it was presented, shoving usually unknown terms like credit default swaps and prime, subprime mortgages and the likes is very hard to do and still keep the attention span of the average viewer, but this movie manages to do it. I love this movie so much, probably one of my all time favorites.
